'''Penguin Computing''' is a computer company headquartered in [[Freemont, California]]. '''Scyld Beowulf''' is a cluster management software package developed by Scyld Software. It is was designed to be deployed to a [[Beowulf (computing)|Beowulf cluster]]. Scyld Software is a subsididary of Penguin Computing.
The company was originally founded in [[San Francisco]] in 1998. It raised $1.7 million in 2006 from Weber Capital, San Francisco Equity Partners and Convergence Ventures.<ref>{{Cite news |title= VC Deals |date= February 7, 2006 |work= PE Week Wire |publisher= Thomson Financial |accessdate= June 3, 2013 |url= http://hosting.mansellgroup.net/enablemail/ThomsonNewLetter/HostedWires/NewsLetters/Feb7-06.htm }}</ref> It raised $1.5 million in funding in 2009 from San Francisco Equity Partners, Convergence Partners, vSpring Capital and Weber Capital.<ref>{{Cite news |title= Penguin Computing snaps up $1.5M for Linux cluster virtualization |date= November 9, 2009 |work= Venture Beat |accessdate= June 3, 2013 |url= http://deals.venturebeat.com/2009/11/09/penguin-computing-snaps-up-1-5m-for-linux-cluster-virtualization/ |deadurl=yes |archivedate= November 13, 2009 |archiveurl= http://web.archive.org/web/20091113144917/http://deals.venturebeat.com/2009/11/09/penguin-computing-snaps-up-1-5m-for-linux-cluster-virtualization/ }}</ref>
The Scyld Beowulf software known as "Scyld ClusterWare 5" was compatible with either [[Red Hat Enterprise Linux]] 5 or [[CentOS]] 5. In 2011 support was broadened to include [[SUSE Linux Enterprise Server]].<ref>{{Cite news |title= Penguin goes hybrid with ClusterWare: Linux meets Windows HPC |work= The Register |author=Timothy Prickett Morgan |date= January 13, 2011 |url= http://www.theregister.co.uk/2011/01/13/penguin_clusterware_hybrid/ |accessdate= June 3, 2013}}</ref>
In 2009, the Penguin on Demand service was announced, which offered [[batch processing]].<ref>{{Cite news |title= Penguin goes hybrid with ClusterWare: InfiniBand with wings |work= The Register |author= Cade Metz |date= August 11, 2009 |url= http://www.theregister.co.uk/2009/08/11/penguin_on_demand/ |accessdate= June 3, 2013}}</ref> In 2012 Penguin Computing announced the UDX1 server that was based on products from [[Calxeda]] intended to run software such as [[Apache Hadoop]].<ref>{{Cite news |title= Penguin Computing muscles into the ARM server fray: Aiming Cortex-A9 clusters at Big Data |work= The Register |author=Timothy Prickett Morgan |date= October 19, 2012 |url= http://www.theregister.co.uk/2012/10/19/penguin_computing_udx1_arm_server/ |accessdate= June 3, 2013}}</ref>
